item.description:
The Four Noble Truths describe the reality of the struggle with life and a way to curb strife through the curbing of craving and the following of the noble eight-fold path.
The Four Noble Truths are:
dukkha (literally &ldquo;suffering&rdquo;; here &ldquo;unsatisfactoriness&rdquo;) is an innate characteristic of existence in the realm of samsara;
samudaya (origin, arising, combination;&lsquo;cause&rsquo;): dukkha arises or continues with tanhā (&ldquo;craving, desire or attachment, lit.&ldquo;thirst&rdquo;). tanhā is traditionally interpreted in western languages as the &lsquo;cause&rsquo; of dukkha , tanha can also be seen as the factor tying us to dukkha, or as a response to dukkha, trying to escape it;
